SIMPLE: intercross
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intercross
<hw>In`ter*cross"</hw> <pr>(?; 115)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Intercrossed</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Intercrossing</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To cross each other, as lines.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>To fertilize by the impregnation
of one species or variety by another; to impregnate by a different
species or variety.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intercross</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Intercross
<hw>In"ter*cross`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The process or
result of cross fertilization between different kinds of animals, or
different varieties of plants.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have reason to believe that occasional <qex>intercrosses</qex>
take place with all animals and plants.</q>
<rj><qau>Darwin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intercrural</ent>⟦br⟧
